    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-12-04T22:40:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-12-04T22:40:00-05:00" n="346"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d346">
                <head>346. Memorandum of Telephone Conversation Between the Under Secretary of State
                    for Political Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_HWA1" type="from"
                        >Harriman</persName>) and the President’s Special Assistant for National
                    Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_BMG1" type="to">Bundy</persName>)<note
                        n="1" type="source" xml:id="d346fn1">Source: Library of Congress, <persName
                            corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> Papers, Telephone Conversations.
                        Transcribed by Dolores Perruso of <persName corresp="#p_HWA1"
                            >Harriman</persName>’s staff.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date"
                            when="1963-12-04T22:40:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 4, 1963—10:40 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>[Here follows discussion of matters unrelated to Vietnam.]</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_BMG1">Bundy</persName> wanted the Gov to know that the
                    President sent a memo to the Secretary<note n="2" xml:id="d346fn2">Not
                        found.</note> saying how strongly he feels about getting a first-rate deputy
                    for <persName corresp="#p_LHCJ1">Lodge</persName>.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> mentioned <persName
                        corresp="#p_NDG1">Nes</persName>.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_BMG1">Bundy</persName> said he got the Gov’s memo of
                    conversation with <persName corresp="#p_LHCJ1">Lodge</persName>.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d346fn3">
                        <p>A memorandum from <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> to
                                <persName corresp="#p_BMG1">Bundy</persName>, December 3, describes
                            the <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName>-<persName
                                corresp="#p_LHCJ1">Lodge</persName> discussion as follows:</p>
                        <p>“I am attaching a copy of a memorandum of my personal talk with <persName
                                corresp="#p_LHCJ1">Cabot Lodge</persName>, which for obvious reasons
                            I am not distributing.</p>
                        <p>“You may want to show the President the last paragraph which relates to
                                <persName corresp="#p_LHCJ1">Cabot</persName>’s personal political
                            thoughts. (Sounds as if <persName corresp="#p_LHCJ1">Cabot</persName>
                            doesn’t think much of the Republican chances next year.)” (Library of
                            Congress, <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> Papers,
                                <persName corresp="#p_BMG1">Bundy</persName>, <persName
                                corresp="#p_BMG1">McGeorge</persName>)</p>
                        <p>The memorandum of conversation between <persName corresp="#p_LHCJ1"
                                >Lodge</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_HWA1"
                                >Harriman</persName> has not been found.</p>
                    </note>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> said he rather agreed with
                        <persName corresp="#p_LHCJ1">Lodge</persName> about the military. <persName
                        corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> said he was told <persName
                        corresp="#p_NDG1">Nes</persName> is a very good man—it is between <persName
                        corresp="#p_NDG1">Nes</persName> and Anschuetz.</p>
                <p>Bill thinks of the two, <persName corresp="#p_NDG1">Nes</persName> is the better.
                        <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> said he talked to Yost. Yost
                    said he was good with military problems and confirmed what <persName
                        corresp="#p_LHCJ1">Lodge</persName> said about Libya. <persName
                        corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> said Bill said what happened when he
                    was there that caused confusion is that <persName corresp="#p_LHCJ1"
                        >Lodge</persName> was taking things into his own hands. <persName
                        corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> said if <persName corresp="#p_LHCJ1"
                        >Lodge</persName> wants <persName corresp="#p_NDG1">Nes</persName>,
                        <persName corresp="#p_NDG1">Nes</persName> is <pb facs="0692" n="666"
                        xml:id="pg_666"/> the best man to do the job. <persName corresp="#p_HWA1"
                        >Harriman</persName> said he wouldn’t support <persName corresp="#p_NDG1"
                        >Nes</persName> unless he had satisfactory reports. A <gloss
                        target="#t_DCM1">DCM</gloss> job is an awful job to take. <persName
                        corresp="#p_NDG1">Nes</persName> would have the advantage of being <persName
                        corresp="#p_LHCJ1">Lodge</persName>’s choice.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_BMG1">Bundy</persName> said <persName corresp="#p_LHCJ1"
                        >Lodge</persName> didn’t distinguish himself in his interview with the
                    President. <persName corresp="#p_BMG1">Bundy</persName> said he thought he was
                    nervous. He thought <persName corresp="#p_LHCJ1">Lodge</persName> may know that
                    the President never thought much of him.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> said it is too bad.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_BMG1">Bundy</persName> said he doesn’t have the operation
                    going.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> said he was concerned about it.
                        <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> said he hoped <persName
                        corresp="#p_BMG1">Bundy</persName> wouldn’t blame <persName
                        corresp="#p_TWC1">Trueheart</persName>.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_BMG1">Bundy</persName> said he had a high opinion of
                        <persName corresp="#p_TWC1">Trueheart</persName>. In the context of the
                    circumstances everybody thought it was better to have a change.</p>
                <p>[Here follows discussion unrelated to Vietnam.]</p>
            </div>
